1
00:00:00,410 --> 00:00:02,745
A good way to develop

2
00:00:02,745 --> 00:00:04,620
a content-based
filtering algorithm

3
00:00:04,620 --> 00:00:06,450
is to use deep learning.

4
00:00:06,450 --> 00:00:09,480
The approach you see in
this video is the way that

5
00:00:09,480 --> 00:00:12,060
many important commercial

6
00:00:12,060 --> 00:00:14,595
state-of-the-art content-based
filtering algorithms

7
00:00:14,595 --> 00:00:16,650
are built today.
Let's take a look.

8
00:00:16,650 --> 00:00:20,505
Recall that in our approach,

9
00:00:20,505 --> 00:00:24,000
given a feature vector
describing a user,

10
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:26,520
such as age and
gender, and country,

11
00:00:26,520 --> 00:00:29,100
and so on, we have to compute

12
00:00:29,100 --> 00:00:32,745
the vector v_u, and similarly,

13
00:00:32,745 --> 00:00:34,934
given a vector describing

14
00:00:34,934 --> 00:00:37,410
a movie such as year of release,

15
00:00:37,410 --> 00:00:39,180
the stars in the
movie, and so on,

16
00:00:39,180 --> 00:00:42,300
we have to compute a vector v_m.

17
00:00:42,300 --> 00:00:45,095
In order to do the former,

18
00:00:45,095 --> 00:00:47,780
we're going to use
a neural network.

19
00:00:47,780 --> 00:00:50,060
The first neural network will

20
00:00:50,060 --> 00:00:53,645
be what we'll call
the user network.

21
00:00:53,645 --> 00:00:56,680
Here's an example
of user network,

22
00:00:56,680 --> 00:00:58,490
that takes as input the list

23
00:00:58,490 --> 00:01:01,010
of features of the user, x_u,

24
00:01:01,010 --> 00:01:02,780
so the age, the gender,

25
00:01:02,780 --> 00:01:05,725
the country of the
user, and so on.

26
00:01:05,725 --> 00:01:08,555
Then using a few layers,

27
00:01:08,555 --> 00:01:10,760
say dense neural network layers,

28
00:01:10,760 --> 00:01:17,360
it will output this vector
v_u that describes the user.

29
00:01:17,360 --> 00:01:20,465
Notice that in this
neural network,

30
00:01:20,465 --> 00:01:24,960
the output layer has 32 units,

31
00:01:24,960 --> 00:01:28,995
and so v_u is actually
a list of 32 numbers.

32
00:01:28,995 --> 00:01:30,690
Unlike most of the
neural networks

33
00:01:30,690 --> 00:01:31,955
that we were using earlier,

34
00:01:31,955 --> 00:01:36,110
the final layer is not
a layer with one unit,

35
00:01:36,110 --> 00:01:38,725
it's a layer with 32 units.

36
00:01:38,725 --> 00:01:44,435
Similarly, to compute
v_m for a movie,

37
00:01:44,435 --> 00:01:47,825
we can have a movie
network as follows,

38
00:01:47,825 --> 00:01:51,365
that takes as input
features of the movie and

39
00:01:51,365 --> 00:01:53,060
through a few layers of

40
00:01:53,060 --> 00:01:56,090
a neural network
is outputting v_m,

41
00:01:56,090 --> 00:01:59,440
that vector that
describes the movie.

42
00:01:59,440 --> 00:02:05,030
Finally, we'll predict the
rating of this user on

43
00:02:05,030 --> 00:02:10,850
that movie as v_ u
dot product with v_m.

44
00:02:10,850 --> 00:02:14,645
Notice that the user network
and the movie network can

45
00:02:14,645 --> 00:02:16,970
hypothetically have
different numbers of

46
00:02:16,970 --> 00:02:18,620
hidden layers and
different numbers

47
00:02:18,620 --> 00:02:20,090
of units per hidden layer.

48
00:02:20,090 --> 00:02:22,190
All the output layer needs to

49
00:02:22,190 --> 00:02:24,845
have the same size of
the same dimension.

50
00:02:24,845 --> 00:02:27,980
In the description
you've seen so far,

51
00:02:27,980 --> 00:02:33,560
we were predicting the 1-5
or 0-5 star movie rating.

52
00:02:33,560 --> 00:02:35,660
If we had binary labels,

53
00:02:35,660 --> 00:02:39,710
if y was to the user
like or favor an item,

54
00:02:39,710 --> 00:02:43,819
then you can also modify
this algorithm to output.

55
00:02:43,819 --> 00:02:46,865
Instead of v_u.v_m,

56
00:02:46,865 --> 00:02:49,040
you can apply the
sigmoid function

57
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:51,170
to that and use this to

58
00:02:51,170 --> 00:02:56,640
predict the probability
that's y^i,j is 1.

59
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:58,610
To flesh out this notation,

60
00:02:58,610 --> 00:03:00,740
we can also add
superscripts i and

61
00:03:00,740 --> 00:03:03,290
j here if we want
to emphasize that

62
00:03:03,290 --> 00:03:06,965
this is the prediction
by user j on movie

63
00:03:06,965 --> 00:03:10,100
i. I've drawn here
the user network

64
00:03:10,100 --> 00:03:13,310
and the movie network as two
separate neural networks.

65
00:03:13,310 --> 00:03:14,960
But it turns out
that we can actually

66
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:16,670
draw them together in

67
00:03:16,670 --> 00:03:20,590
a single diagram as if it
was a single neural network.

68
00:03:20,590 --> 00:03:22,635
This is what it looks like.

69
00:03:22,635 --> 00:03:25,850
On the upper portion
of this diagram,

70
00:03:25,850 --> 00:03:28,145
we have the user network which

71
00:03:28,145 --> 00:03:31,670
inputs x_u and ends
up computing v_u.

72
00:03:31,670 --> 00:03:34,250
On the lower portion
of this diagram,

73
00:03:34,250 --> 00:03:36,740
we have what was
the movie network,

74
00:03:36,740 --> 00:03:40,465
the input is x_m and
ends up computing v_m,

75
00:03:40,465 --> 00:03:45,335
and these two vectors are
then dot-product together.

76
00:03:45,335 --> 00:03:47,930
This dot here
represents dot product,

77
00:03:47,930 --> 00:03:51,635
and this gives us
our prediction.

78
00:03:51,635 --> 00:03:56,015
Now, this model has
a lot of parameters.

79
00:03:56,015 --> 00:03:58,490
Each of these layers of
a neural network has

80
00:03:58,490 --> 00:04:01,345
a usual set of parameters
of the neural network.

81
00:04:01,345 --> 00:04:04,470
How do you train all
the parameters of

82
00:04:04,470 --> 00:04:08,610
both the user network
and the movie network?

83
00:04:08,610 --> 00:04:13,235
What we're going to do is
construct a cost function J,

84
00:04:13,235 --> 00:04:15,470
which is going to
be very similar to

85
00:04:15,470 --> 00:04:16,670
the cost function that you

86
00:04:16,670 --> 00:04:18,455
saw in collaborative filtering,

87
00:04:18,455 --> 00:04:20,990
which is assuming
that you do have

88
00:04:20,990 --> 00:04:24,860
some data of some users
having rated some movies,

89
00:04:24,860 --> 00:04:27,590
we're going to sum
over all pairs i and

90
00:04:27,590 --> 00:04:30,905
j of where you have labels,

91
00:04:30,905 --> 00:04:32,615
where i,j equals 1

92
00:04:32,615 --> 00:04:36,270
of the difference
between the prediction.

93
00:04:36,270 --> 00:04:40,440
That would be v_u^j
dot product with

94
00:04:40,440 --> 00:04:46,455
v_m^i minus y^ij squared.

95
00:04:46,455 --> 00:04:49,475
The way we would
train this model

96
00:04:49,475 --> 00:04:53,000
is depending on the parameters
of the neural network,

97
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,730
you end up with
different vectors

98
00:04:55,730 --> 00:04:58,960
here for the users
and for the movies.

99
00:04:58,960 --> 00:05:02,090
What we'd like to do is
train the parameters

100
00:05:02,090 --> 00:05:04,760
of the neural network
so that you end up with

101
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:08,720
vectors for the users and for
the movies that results in

102
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:12,895
small squared error into
predictions you get out here.

103
00:05:12,895 --> 00:05:15,380
To be clear, there's

104
00:05:15,380 --> 00:05:17,915
no separate training procedure

105
00:05:17,915 --> 00:05:20,285
for the user and movie networks.

106
00:05:20,285 --> 00:05:22,055
This expression down here,

107
00:05:22,055 --> 00:05:25,205
this is the cost
function used to train

108
00:05:25,205 --> 00:05:29,090
all the parameters of the
user and the movie networks.

109
00:05:29,090 --> 00:05:32,120
We're going to judge the two
networks according to how

110
00:05:32,120 --> 00:05:36,100
well v_u and v_m predict y^ij,

111
00:05:36,100 --> 00:05:38,135
and with this cost function,

112
00:05:38,135 --> 00:05:40,520
we're going to use
gradient descent or

113
00:05:40,520 --> 00:05:43,070
some other optimization
algorithm to tune

114
00:05:43,070 --> 00:05:45,380
the parameters of the
neural network to cause

115
00:05:45,380 --> 00:05:48,640
the cost function J to
be as small as possible.

116
00:05:48,640 --> 00:05:51,335
If you want to
regularize this model,

117
00:05:51,335 --> 00:05:53,720
we can also add the usual neural

118
00:05:53,720 --> 00:05:56,270
network regularization term to

119
00:05:56,270 --> 00:05:58,370
encourage the neural
networks to keep

120
00:05:58,370 --> 00:06:01,570
the values of their
parameters small.

121
00:06:01,570 --> 00:06:04,115
It turns out, after you've
trained this model,

122
00:06:04,115 --> 00:06:07,640
you can also use this
to find similar items.

123
00:06:07,640 --> 00:06:09,740
This is akin to
what we have seen

124
00:06:09,740 --> 00:06:12,215
with collaborative
filtering features,

125
00:06:12,215 --> 00:06:13,850
helping you find similar items

126
00:06:13,850 --> 00:06:16,560
as well. Let's take a look.

127
00:06:16,720 --> 00:06:21,030
V_u^j is a vector of
length 32 that describes

128
00:06:21,030 --> 00:06:25,035
a user j that have
features x_ u^j.

129
00:06:25,035 --> 00:06:29,775
Similarly, v^i_m is a vector

130
00:06:29,775 --> 00:06:31,590
of length 32 that describes

131
00:06:31,590 --> 00:06:34,920
a movie with these
features over here.

132
00:06:34,920 --> 00:06:37,140
Given a specific movie,

133
00:06:37,140 --> 00:06:41,490
what if you want to find
other movies similar to it?

134
00:06:41,490 --> 00:06:48,135
Well, this vector v^i_m
describes the movie i.

135
00:06:48,135 --> 00:06:51,425
If you want to find other
movies similar to it,

136
00:06:51,425 --> 00:06:56,944
you can then look for other
movies k so that the distance

137
00:06:56,944 --> 00:06:59,030
between the vector describing

138
00:06:59,030 --> 00:07:02,510
movie k and the vector
describing movie i,

139
00:07:02,510 --> 00:07:05,920
that the squared
distance is small.

140
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:09,380
This expression plays
a role similar to what

141
00:07:09,380 --> 00:07:12,740
we had previously with
collaborative filtering,

142
00:07:12,740 --> 00:07:16,790
where we talked about finding
a movie with features

143
00:07:16,790 --> 00:07:21,095
x^k that was similar
to the features x^i.

144
00:07:21,095 --> 00:07:22,715
Thus, with this approach,

145
00:07:22,715 --> 00:07:26,950
you can also find items
similar to a given item.

146
00:07:26,950 --> 00:07:31,560
One final note, this can be
pre-computed ahead of time.

147
00:07:31,560 --> 00:07:32,885
By that I mean,

148
00:07:32,885 --> 00:07:36,410
you can run a compute
server overnight to

149
00:07:36,410 --> 00:07:37,955
go through the list of

150
00:07:37,955 --> 00:07:40,130
all your movies and
for every movie,

151
00:07:40,130 --> 00:07:44,330
find similar movies to
it, so that tomorrow,

152
00:07:44,330 --> 00:07:46,190
if a user comes to
the website and

153
00:07:46,190 --> 00:07:48,245
they're browsing
a specific movie,

154
00:07:48,245 --> 00:07:50,580
you can already have
pre-computed to

155
00:07:50,580 --> 00:07:52,655
10 or 20 most similar movies

156
00:07:52,655 --> 00:07:54,560
to show to the
user at that time.

157
00:07:54,560 --> 00:07:57,080
The fact that you can
pre-compute ahead of

158
00:07:57,080 --> 00:07:59,780
time what's similar
to a given movie,

159
00:07:59,780 --> 00:08:01,310
will turn out to be important

160
00:08:01,310 --> 00:08:03,260
later when we talk about scaling

161
00:08:03,260 --> 00:08:07,880
up this approach to a very
large catalog of movies.

162
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:10,775
That's how you can use
deep learning to build

163
00:08:10,775 --> 00:08:13,975
a content-based
filtering algorithm.

164
00:08:13,975 --> 00:08:15,950
You might remember when we

165
00:08:15,950 --> 00:08:17,720
were talking about
decision trees

166
00:08:17,720 --> 00:08:18,830
and the pros and cons of

167
00:08:18,830 --> 00:08:21,180
decision trees versus
neural networks.

168
00:08:21,180 --> 00:08:23,210
I mentioned that one
of the benefits of

169
00:08:23,210 --> 00:08:26,285
neural networks is that
it's easier to take

170
00:08:26,285 --> 00:08:27,680
multiple neural networks and

171
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:28,970
put them together to make them

172
00:08:28,970 --> 00:08:32,125
work in console to
build a larger system.

173
00:08:32,125 --> 00:08:35,450
What you just saw was
actually an example of that,

174
00:08:35,450 --> 00:08:37,910
where we could take
a user network and

175
00:08:37,910 --> 00:08:40,310
the movie network and
put them together,

176
00:08:40,310 --> 00:08:42,935
and then take the inner
product of the outputs.

177
00:08:42,935 --> 00:08:44,480
This ability to put

178
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:47,690
two neural networks
together this how we've

179
00:08:47,690 --> 00:08:49,085
managed to come up with

180
00:08:49,085 --> 00:08:50,885
a more complex architecture

181
00:08:50,885 --> 00:08:53,405
that turns out to
be quite powerful.

182
00:08:53,405 --> 00:08:55,010
One notes, if you're

183
00:08:55,010 --> 00:08:56,975
implementing these
algorithms in practice,

184
00:08:56,975 --> 00:08:58,940
I find that developers often

185
00:08:58,940 --> 00:09:01,040
end up spending a lot
of time carefully

186
00:09:01,040 --> 00:09:03,470
designing the features
needed to feed

187
00:09:03,470 --> 00:09:06,130
into these content-based
filtering algorithms.

188
00:09:06,130 --> 00:09:08,740
If we end up building one of
these systems commercially,

189
00:09:08,740 --> 00:09:11,090
it may be worth
spending some time

190
00:09:11,090 --> 00:09:15,420
engineering good features for
this application as well.

191
00:09:15,680 --> 00:09:19,100
In terms of these applications,

192
00:09:19,100 --> 00:09:20,720
one limitation
that the algorithm

193
00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:22,550
as we've described
it is it can be

194
00:09:22,550 --> 00:09:25,550
computationally very
expensive to run if you have

195
00:09:25,550 --> 00:09:27,290
a large catalog of a lot of

196
00:09:27,290 --> 00:09:29,720
different movies you
may want to recommend.

197
00:09:29,720 --> 00:09:32,210
In the next video, let's
take a look at some of

198
00:09:32,210 --> 00:09:34,340
the practical issues
and how you can modify

199
00:09:34,340 --> 00:09:37,040
this algorithm to make a
scale that are working

200
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:40,205
on even very large
item catalogs.

201
00:09:40,205 --> 00:09:43,260
Let's go see that
